1) Delete
By default, the delete operation will do a DETACH DELETE,
which means it will first delete any relationships connected to the node before deleting the node itself.
However, the node at the other end of the relationship will not get deleted.

2) Repository:
Spring Data Neo4j also implements a few standard methods, such as save, findById, findAll, and deleteById

3)
movieRepo.findAll(); - returns Node with Relationsa nd related Nodes

it is equal to:
@Query("MATCH (m:Movie)<-[r:ACTED_IN]-(p:Person)" +
            "RETURN m, collect(r), collect(p) LIMIT 20;")
    Iterable<Movie> findMoviesSubset();

But if you just specify:
@Query("MATCH (m:Movie)<-[r:ACTED_IN]-(p:Person)" +
            "RETURN m LIMIT 20;")
    Iterable<Movie> findMoviesSubsetNoRelations();
Then only nodes and they properties would be returned, no relations


4) Projection:
Reducing database load for entities containing lots of properties that may not always be needed.
-Interface based projections: MovieProjection - to get subset of return data
Iterable<MovieProjection> findAllMovieProjectionsBy();

-DTO-based projections really shine when you want to add additional properties to an entity: MovieDTOProjection
@Query("MATCH (m:Movie)<-[r:ACTED_IN]-(p:Person) " +
            "RETURN m, COUNT(p) AS castSize LIMIT 10;")
    Iterable<MovieDTOProjection> findAllDTOProjectionsWithCustomQuery();

